    <li>
        <div style="font-weight:bold">Head-Heavy:</div>
  <br>
  As the control of head-heavy rackets takes more effort and practice to
   master, these rackets are recommended for experienced players vs.
    beginners.<br>

  <span style="color:rgb(1, 255, 1)">Pros: </span>Generates powerful shots<br>
 <span style="color:rgb(255, 5, 5)"> Cons:</span> Decreased racket handling, Increased risk of injury if misused.<br>
  Recommended for: Attacking players, Back-court play.
  
  
</li>
<br>
<li>
    
    <div style="font-weight:bold">Even-balanced:</div>
<br> Jack of all trades when it comes to rackets  , mixes the 
characteristics of head heavy and light type of rackets thus giving an
 all round style of playing . Thus best suited for beginners to help them
  discover their playing style and for players without any specific
   preference.<br>
   <span style="color:rgb(4, 255, 4)"> Pros:</span> Capable of executing each kind of shot to some extent<br>
    <span style="color:red">Cons:</span> No specialization towards either defensive or offensive extremes<br>
Recommended for: All around players, Beginners.

</li>
</ul>
